The PRINCE2 Framework-How it aligns or differs from APM and PMBOK?
3rd of July,2023
Author: Sruthi Akhil (23819557)
The PRINCE2 Framework
The PRINCE2 is an effective project management methodology which is recognised and widely
adopted by the government of the United Kingdom and popular in Europe. PRINCE2 stands for
PRojects IN Controlled Environments which involves a high degree of early-stage planning. This
is a structured project management methodology, where a project is ordered into defined steps so
that the project ends up organized and perfect. It has been proven from experiences that
unorganised, poorly controlled projects normally end up lamentably wrong. Citing an example of
such a project here. Its the London Ambulance Services automation project which experienced
system failures and debt explosion. Structured project management methods exist to prevent such
disasters.
The PRINCE2 framework says that a project should have:
A plan and must be organised beforehand.
Be maintained properly, organised and controlled.
A controlled end i.e., once the project is done, we must check for its completeness and take
any necessary actions if required.
The PRINCE2 Project Management roles include:
PRINCE2 has a framework that helps organizations to manage projects more effectively. It helps
in improving project management skills and knowledge. Provides better communication between
project teams and stakeholders. We have improved risk management strategies, better control over
project resources and improved project planning and monitoring.

The APM
APM stands for Application Performance Management. It is the monitoring and management of
the performance and availability of software applications. APM strives to detect and diagnose
complex application performance problems to maintain an expected level of service. In project
management, APM is the UK-based professional organization that provides a structured approach
to developing project management competencies and advancing careers in the field. The APM
approach is based on two key resources: the Body of Knowledge (Bok) and Competence
Framework. APM is the only chartered membership organisation for the project profession in the
world.
PMBOK
PMBOK stands for Project Management Body of Knowledge. It is a set of standard terminology
and guidelines for project management. It provides a framework for managing projects that
includes processes, tools, and techniques to help manage projects effectively. PMBOK is not a
methodology but rather a guide to project management. The body of knowledge evolves over time
and is presented in A Guide to the Project Management Body of Knowledge (PMBOK Guide), a
book whose seventh edition was released in 2021.
How do these align or differ?
PRINCE2 methodology provides a framework covering the variety of activities required within a
project. It is a process-based approach for project management providing a customised and
expandable method for the management of all types of projects. It also provides a common
language for project management that can be used across different industries and sectors. PMBOK
provides a framework for managing projects that includes processes, tools, and techniques to help
manage projects effectively. PRINCE2 and PMBOK are both frameworks for project management.
PRINCE2 is a methodology while PMBOK is a guide to project management.
PRINCE2 and PMBOK have some similarities in terms of their approach to project management.
Both frameworks provide guidance on how to manage projects effectively and both frameworks
are widely used across different industries and sectors. However, there are also some differences
between the two frameworks. For example, PRINCE2 places more emphasis on the business case
for a project while PMBOK places more emphasis on the project scope. The business case is a
key component of PRINCE2. It is a document that outlines the justification for a project and
provides a framework for decision-making throughout the project lifecycle. The business case
includes information on the costs and benefits of the project, as well as an assessment of the risks
involved. The business case is used to ensure that the project remains practical and that it continues
to deliver value to the organization throughout its lifecycle. The project scope is a key component
of PMBOK. It defines the boundaries of the project and outlines what is included and what is
excluded from the project. The project scope is used to ensure that the project remains focused on
its objectives and that it delivers the expected outcomes. The project scope is defined in the project
charter and is used throughout the project lifecycle to guide decision-making and to ensure that
the project remains on track.
The business case and project scope are both important components of project management.
